@endnode

@node "Needs" "Needs"
An Amiga with Arexx & Thor running.

Join & Type commands somewhere in your path.

The current article should be spam or UCE.

Some common sense about which addresses to complain to.

OS 3.0 (for correct syntax when using echo)

@{"traceroute" link "tr" 0} (the assumptions in the script are from the traceroute that comes
with AmiTCP. If you have a problem then mail me)

tail (available from Aminet as headtail) to maintain the traceroute database.
You could use a rollover file with AFS.
@endnode

@node "INSTALL" "Installation"
Use the supplied Install arexx script if you are new to TASC!

If you have used TASC before it's better to install it by hand to avoid
overwriting your spam.db and spamaddr. @{b}Please note that starting with v2.0
@{u}spamaddr@{uu} has been moved from @{u}rexx/@{uu} to @{u}db/@{uu}!@{ub}

Copy the files in rexx/ to your thor/rexx directory.
    TASC.thor
    SpamMailHeader
    SpamNewsHeader
    Altspam.thor
    Gooddomain.thor

Make a directory called 'db' in your ThorDataPath (i.e. the same directory
that holds the 'BBS0' & 'decoded' directories).

Copy the files in db/ to the above directory.
    Spam.db
    Spamaddr


You do not need to create an ENVAR:Thor/TASC.CFG (copied in ENV:Thor/ too :-)
as I think the default values are pretty good. You may create it later...

Assign function keys in Thor to the TASC scripts.

Copy the traceroute scripts & install them in your AmiTCP/Miami set up, to be
run each time that you go online.

Read this guide file.
@endnode

@node "CONFIG" "Configuration"
                     @{b}@{u}ENV:thor/TASC.Cfg@{ub}@{uu}

I'll get around to writing a congiguration script one day, honest. In the
interim, you'll have to get out your text editor.

@{u}delmsg:@{uu} (Y/N) default N

Set this to 'Y' if you want the spam deleted as soon as you have finished
with it. @{i}For reasons I don't understand the deleted flag is not set in Thor's
window, although the message is deleted as planned.@{ui}

@{u}urg:@{uu} (Y/N) default N

Set to 'Y' to send your email complaints with the urgent flag set.

@{u}mailhd:@{uu} default "Email spam"

The subject for your complaints about email abuse

@{u}newshd:@{uu} default "Usenet spam/mail fraud"

The subject for yor complaints about Usenet abuse

@{u}globPM:@{uu} (Y/N) default N

Do you want to always send your complaints to the postmaster?

@{u}SkipName:@{uu} (Y/N) default Y

I think that usually it's unuseful to put the retrieved string as "names", if
you do not agree with me simply set this switch to "N" and everything will be
as the previuos versione! :-)

@{u}Postmaster:@{uu} default @{i}blank@{ui}

If you set this to your email domain then you will send your complaints as
'Postmaster@<domain>'. Obviously, don't try this if you don't have your own
domain, you'll only upset the real postmasters.

@{u}database:@{uu} default "spam.db"

Where do you want to keep the database of redirected & undeliverable email
addresses? (Location is relative to your Thor data path & assumes that you
have a directory there called 'db')

@{u}SRCHBODY:@{uu} (Y/N) default N

Switch to allow searching of the message body for addresses to complain to,
as well as the headers.

Then 4 variables to allow the @{"traceroute commands" link "tr" 0} to work:

@{u}TRACER:@{uu} (Y/N) default N

Variable to allow you to switch the traceroute calls on & off

@{u}TRACETMP:@{uu} default "traceroute.tmp"

The name of the file that the traceroute requests should be stored in.

@{u}TRACEFI:@{uu} default "spamtrace.db"

The name of the file that the traceroute output will be stored in. This is
also specified relative to {thordatapath}/db

@{u}TRACELEN:@{uu} default 3000

The number of lines of traceroute output that you would like to keep. The
database only uses complete traceroute output, so allow enough room here so
that the data is still there when a bounce gets back to you.


Finally 2 variables for Altspam to use:

@{u}Bounce:@{uu} default @{i}blank@{ui}

The email domain used by your postmaster to return undelivered email to you
in case this & your domain address are different).

@{u}Mine:@{uu} default @{i}blank@{ui}

Your domain name for the check with Bounce:



                       @{b}@{u}The Headers@{ub}@{uu}

There are two files in this package (spammailheader & spamnewsheader) that
are automatically put at the top of your complaint. These contain the actual
complaint text that will be read by the postmaster/official agency that you
send the complaint to.

Feel free to edit them if you prefer a different literary approach.



                        @{b}@{u}SpamAddr@{ub}@{uu}

This file contains the additional email addresses for the official agencies
etc. that you might want to forward your complaint to. Let me know if you
find any additional email addresses to add to this file.

To add new addresses you will need to use a text editor. Please note the
format of the file: First a '+' then the name of the agency then a ':' & then
the email address. Note that there should be @{b}no@{ub} spaces after the ':'.



                         @{b}@{u}Spam.db@{ub}@{uu}

This contains the redirection information that allows TASC.thor to help you
avoid continually sending complaints to postmasters who don't care, or to
machines that can't deliver the complaint. Again, you can add things by hand.
The format for the entries in the database is:

{bad address}->{Good address}

(Note the lack of spaces. This entry will change the address that you are
offered, from the bad to the good one. Redirected addresses are marked as
such, to avoid confusion.)

or

{bad address}->Undeliverable

(This entry prevents you from trying to send to this machine/domain again).

or {bad address}->Faked

This triggers a search for a possible mailserver on the preceeding Received:
line. The preceeding line's addresses are still offered, but requests will
not be sent out to the domain that was marked as faked.

or {good address}->8-}

This flags the domain as being responsive to your complaints. It's there
mostly to highlight where might be good to send your message. There is no
functional change with this entry.
@endnode

@node "USE" "Usage"
 Display the headers of the spam/UCE before calling the script - that way you
can get a feel for how useful it will be to complain to the addresses that
TASC provides. Spammers fake various bits of the headers & I can see no way
that a script can predict all of these. 

@{b}@{u}Easy@{ub}@{uu} - assign TASC to a function key. Get spam. Call TASC. Select addresses
to complain to. Send complaint. All done.

@{b}@{u}Hard@{ub}@{uu} - The parsing of mail/news headers is not an exact science when dealing
with spam. It's not unknown for all of the @{i}text@{ui} descriptions of the
originating computer to be faked. The IP address (the set of 4 numbers with
dots between them) @{i}can@{ui} be more reliable.

TASC will parse out as many potential email addresses related to the origin
of the spam as it can. It will ignore duplicated addresses & automatically
complains to the postmaster of the machines that you select (Unless you have
set it up to use a different user name for that specific domain).

Which addresses you choose is up to you - the From:, Reply-To: & Return:
addresses are the weakest links. Message-ID: NNTP-Posting-Host: & both
addresses offered for MailServer are probably the most reliable.

@{b}Beware@{ub} not even these addresses are infallible - spammers have been know to
add a fake Received: line to their mail headers, confusing the parsing
mechanism of TASC. Using Altspam you can record your failed attempts & stop
them happening again.

@{"I've added some new tools to help with this" link "New" 0}

@{b}@{u}Important @{ub}@{uu} TASC will automatically offer the mail addresses of the postmaster
of the parent of the spammers mailing domain (e.g. using my address you would
be offered 'u-net.com' as well as 'toadhall.u-net.com'). This option is not
to be used lightly - ideally not until you have failed to get a satisfactory
answer from the address further down the hierachy. It sometimes fails too:
blob.ac.uk will be truncated to ac.uk, despite this being an inappropriate
domain - the overhead needed to check for all possible variations of this
make it pointless trying to avoid these occurences.

@{i}P.S. @{ui} A rudimentary automated complaint function was added right at the start
of TASC, but never documented. Feel free to use it if you like. It's not that
good & I'm planning on removing it soon, so it won't get any better!
@endnode

@node "WHAT" "What does it do?"
 Usenet Spam & Unsolicited Junk Email are a real pain. Left unchecked they
will eventually make the internet almost unusable (they cost next to nothing,
so unlike paper junk mail there is no incentive for the spammers to aim for
their target population).

The only way to stop these spammers is to complain about them & have their
accounts closed down. This is where TASC comes in.

TASC reads the header data that is sent with the spam message & extracts any
potential internet address that a complaint could be sent to. It then
presents these addresses (after removing any obvious duplicates &
substituting addresses where it knows that a complaint is pointless) for you
to decide which ones you want to send a complaint to (along with a copy of
the spam).

TASC also reads in a file of official agencies email addresses & offers them
in addition to the addresses from the headers.

TASC will optionally autodelete the spam from your database, after writing
the complaint, so that you never need to see it again.

@{"How does it do it?" link "Howdo" 0}
@endnode

@node "How" "does"
 The information on the route that the spam took & the person who sent it are
kept in the header of the message. Thor usually hides this from you, but can
display it in the message view window if you click on the top button on the
right hand side of the window.

TASC parses domain names from the header of the spam using the following
system:

@{u}Mailserver:@{uu} Parses each Received: line until there are no more. This should
be the first machine that the message passed through. Domain names & IP
addresses are extracted & presented. @{i}Beware, spammers have been known to add
a fake Received: line to the headers. You may need to ignore this domain name
if you can see evidence of a dial up connection on the preceeding received:
line. @{ui}

@{u}From:@{uu} The domain that you see at the top of the message. No often reliable.
Parsed out from the one entry in the header.

@{u}Message ID:@{uu} Often not a bad source of information on the true domain that the
spam originates from. Can be faked however. Parsed out from the one entry in
the header.

@{u}Reply to: @{uu} Often a waste of time, but sometimes gets set to a real address
when the spammer wants to get the replies. Parsed out from the one entry in
the header.

@{u}Return Path:@{uu} This almost never points to a real domain, but it's here none
the less. Parsed out from the one entry in the header.

@{u}Path:@{uu} Only applies to news spam. Parsed out in the same basic way that the
mailserver address is.

@{u}NNTP:@{uu} This is the news equivalent of the message ID. It is found in the same
way.

@{u}Body(Email):@{uu} Any email address domain found in the body of the spam/UCE.

@{u}Body(http):@{uu} Any http domain found in the body of the spam/UCE.
@endnode

